            <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" width="100%">
              <tr> 
                <td bgcolor="#004142" height="12" valign="top" width="44%"><img src="../global/images/tables/circuit/topleft.GIF" width="11" height="15" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
                <td bgcolor="#004142" align="right" valign="top" height="12" width="48%"><img src="../global/images/tables/circuit/topright.GIF" width="12" height="15" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Careful Planning</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2333"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2333"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=5695">Troy "Rycar & Boy" Drinkard</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 5695 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A look at a forgotten card.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">   Ever since Enhanced Jabba&#146;s Palace, Careful Planning has been tossed aside as waste and No Escape food. The last time I saw it in a deck was in &quot;Odds Beating Ewoks&quot; on Decipher and Throne Room Mains decks seen all over. However, it is still a tournament worthy card based on its Used effect alone.<br>
   First, though, let&#146;s look at its potential as a Starting Interrupt. The first thing that I noticed is that it starts and returns to your reserve deck as a recycleable five destiny. Simple. But secondly, it has many uses for getting out important locations that can&#146;t be pulled for normally. If you are playing a mixed space/ground deck and don&#146;t have the setup for A New Secret Base or Hidden Base, Combat Readiness can allow you to start an important System and still get nice force activation and places to set up your forces.<br>
   An option open to you is Roche. You could start Roche and play Careful Planning to also pull Farm and Jungle. Now you have five force on your first turn and can pull two more locations (the Big One and the Asteroid Cave) for two more force, seven on your second turn, plus what the DS gives you.<br>
   Want to start a Musicians/odds deck? Well, you know you want Clak&#146;dor VII to get destiny +2 on your Biths, and you also need a place for your Biths to sit. The best way to be able to pull both of these is Careful Planning. You start Clak&#146;dor VII and again pull two generic sites.<br>
   There are other tournament worthy options, and fun decks that you can make by starting mixed locations with Careful Planning, but another tournament worthy option is converting your opponent&#146;s sites. Let&#146;s take a look:<br>
   If you are playing a Harvest deck and want to garauntee that you get Lars&#146; Moisture Farm out, but still get extra force, perhaps you would start Careful Planning to pull an extra Tatooine site. Wanna choke Scum? Well, if they&#146;re playing Court, just stock in a Tatooine: Jabba&#146;s Palace to prevent them from searching for other sites. Playing My Kind Of Scum? Don&#146;t want them to get an alien out? Convert their Audience Chamber before the game begins.<br>
   Now that we&#146;ve taken a look at the Starting uses of this card, let&#146;s take a look at it being used:<br>
   NEWBIES PLEASE READ: Tracking was a very new concept to me when I branched out of friendly play and began to post on DeckTech and Decipher. I couldn&#146;t track at all, but including this card in my deck helped. Here&#146;s how:<br>
   Now I understand this won&#146;t help some of you more mature players, but it did help me. I want it to help others. I began learning how to track one card. That&#146;s it; one card. I then used this card to help me get to that card everytime a battle was initiated. I would follow a five everywhere it went, and then I would play Careful Planning to activate down to it. You see, Used: Draw two destiny and activate UP TO that much force. You don&#146;t have to activate it all, and if you drew a high enough destiny you can use it to bring your tracked card to the top. Also, now you have enough force to use and fire a Blaster Rifle or other EPP weapon and blast their Vader away with your destiny that you will have. Even more, you have a five destiny back in your deck, and it&#146;s ready to be drawn again later.<br>
   Okay, mature SW:CCG players, did that not help you? Well, are you playing a Hunt Down deck while they&#146;ve been tracking your cards and ready to initiate a duel when you have a low destiny? Are you ready with a Glancing Blow and Courage Of a Skywalker, but, suddenly, they have Grand Moff Tarkin and initiate a battle, so they can cancel even your added destiny? Well, hey, a battle was just initiated, so surprise them with Careful Planning to activate down to your high card! Winning the duel usually means winnning the game that I&#146;ve seen!<br>
   Is the opponent playing First Strike and you aren&#146;t gonna be able to play Hyper Escape, Narrow Escape, Fallen Portal, Houjix, or some other game saving interrupt? Well, Careful Planning can give you the force to use it, and give you a nice destiny on top for Fallen Portal or the like.<br>
   Using Careful Planning as a Starting Interrupt has lost its power. No Escape has come around, and playing generic sites is a risk. No Escape is found in Court decks, Hunt Down decks, and Bring Him Before Me decks. These three, as well as other decks that put it in randomly, can hurt you when you play an odd deck using Careful Planning, but you can still use it to get an extra non-generic site out, and it is still powerful as a used interrupt.<br>
   I hope that I&#146;ve helped newbies and advanced players alike. That&#146;s usually hard to do. Thanks for looking. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2333"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2333"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2333" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
